manual/dashboard/dashboard_intro.html.title: Dashboard
manual/dashboard/dashboard_intro.html.body:
Dashboard
The "Dashboard" page of Iota provides an overview of the list of projects contained in the database of the user. Each project is represented as a rectangular accordion that shows the title of the project and the last date when the project was modified (see Figure 1). 
Users can filter the list of projects by means of the "Search by title" bar located at the top of the windonw. Moreover, the projects can be sorted by different options (Title, Created Date, Modified Date and Last Accessed Date) using the combo box located at the right side of the search bar.  
Users can get more detailed information about the contents of the projects by click on their correspondent accordion:

Description
Created date
Number of items of each project's assets type:
Scenarios
Screenshots
Videos
Graphs
Meshes
Variables


Tags

 
Figure 1 - "Dashboard" page where the list of projects is shown
Creating a new project
A new project can be created by clicking on Add Project button located at top left of screen (see Figure 1). After clicking on the button, the "Create Project" window shows up with the following fields:

Name: users need to provide a name for the project.
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the project.
Tags (optional): mulitple tags/keywords can be associated with the project by using commas (for instace: DEM, COHESIVE, SILO)

 
Figure 2 - Pop-up window to create a new project
Editing a project's info
The basic info of the project ("Title", "Description" and "Tags") can be edited by using the option "Edit Project". This is accessible by clicking on the "More" button located at the right corner of the projects' accordions.
Deleting a project
Users can delete an existing project from their database by means of the option "Delete Project" that is accessible after clicking on the "More" button located at the right corner of the projects' accordions.
Loading a project
Users can load projects by means of the "Load" button that appears at the right corner of the projects' accordions (see Figure 1). After clicking on the "Load" button, the project will be autotmatically loaded and the "Project" page will be shown on the screen.

manual/project/project_intro.html.title: Project
manual/project/project_intro.html.body:
Project
The "Project" page provides information about the items associated with the project. The page is mainly divided into the following sections (see Figure 3):

Title and Description of the project. 
Global: this section shows rectangular accordions for the different type of assets associated with the 
project:
Datasets
Screenshots
Graphs
Meshes
Videos
Files
Variables


Scenarios: this section shows the list of scenarios associated with the project.
Thumbnail: users can select an image to be used as thumbnail for the project. 
Additional information:
User Name: name of the user who created the project.
Created Date: project's creation date.
Last Modified: Latest data when the project was modified.
Tags




_Figure 3 - Example of the "Project"

manual/project/project_datasets.html.title: Datasets
manual/project/project_datasets.html.body:
Datasets
A dataset represents the data coming from a simulation (DEM, CFD, FEM, ...) or the data of a coarse-graining analysis generated by the coarse-graining module. Each dataset is represented as a rectangle containing the name and type of dataset (see Figure 4) 
Importing a dataset
Users can import datasets by clicking on the Import button located at the right corner of "Datasets" accordion and selecting the type of dataset to be imported (see Figure 4). A pop-up window will be shown in order introduce the following fields for the dataset:

Name: users needs to provide a name for the dataset.
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the dataset.
Scenario: users can associate the dataset to an existent scenario of the project1.
Type: specify the format of the dataset to be imported2. 
File: the icon located at the right side opens a file browser window that allows users to select the file to import the dataset.


1. Coarse-graining dataset need to be associated with an existent scenario. ↩


2. Currently, only datasets with Particle Analytics' formats "padem" and "pacg" can be imported by means of the mechanism. In order to import DEM datasets from other formats (EDEM, P4X, LIGGGHTS), please see here. ↩

Visualising a dataset
Users can visualise a dataset by clicking on the Load button that appears when users are hovering the rectangle of the corresponding dataset (see Figure 4). This action will load the dataset into ""Post" page of Iota. 

Figure 4 - Example of "Datasets" section at "Project" page

manual/project/project_screenshots.html.title: Screenshots
manual/project/project_screenshots.html.body:
Screenshots
This section shows the screenshots/images associated with the project/scenario. The images can have been generated by using the screenshot feature provided in Iota or they can be imported from files with a supported image format (png, jpg and gif).   
 
Figure 5 - "Screenshots" sections of Iota
Importing a screenshot
Users can import image files (png extension) by clicking on the Import button located at the right corner of "Screenshots" accordion (see Figure 5). A pop-up window will be shown in order introduce the following fields for the screenshot:

Name: users needs to provide a name for the screenshot.
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the screenshot.
Scenario (optional): users can associate the screenshot to an existent scenario of the project.
File: the icon located at the right side opens a file browser window that allows users to select the image file to be imported.

 
Figure 6 - Import Screenshot window

manual/project/project_graphs.html.title: Graphs
manual/project/project_graphs.html.body:
Graphs
This section contains the graphs associated with the project/scenario. Graphs can be generated by using the tools provided by Iota or they can be imported from csv files.
 
Figure 7 - "Graphs" section of Iota
Importing a Graph
Users can import graphs from csv files by clicking on the Import button located at the right corner of "Graphs" accordion when this is expanded (see Figure 7). A pop-up window will be shonw in order introduce the following fields for the graph:

Name: users needs to provide a name for the graph. It will be used as title for the graph.
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the graph.
Scenario (optional): users can use the combo box to associate the graph to a scenario of the project.
File: the icon located at the right side opens a file browser window that allows users to select the csv file to be imported.

 
Figure 8 - "Import Graph" window
Loading a Graph
Users can load the graphs into the the "Graph" page of Iota by clicking on the Load button that appears when users are hovering the thumbnail of each graph (see Figure 7). This action will load the graph into the "Graph" page of the software where users can perform advanced customization of the graph.

manual/project/project_videos.html.title: Videos
manual/project/project_videos.html.body:
Videos
This section shows the videos associated with the project/scenario. The videos may have been generated by using the record animation feature provided in "Post" page or they can be imported from files with a supported video format. 
 
Figure 11 - "Videos" section of Iota
Importing a video from a File
Users can import a video from a file by clicking on the Import button located at the right corner of "Videos" accordion (see Figure 11). A pop-up window will be shown in order introduce the following fields for the video:

Name: users needs to provide a name for the video.
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the video.
Scenario (optional): users can associate the video to an existent scenario of the project.
File: the icon located at the right side opens a file browser window that allows users to select the video file to be imported.

 
Figure 12 - Import Video window

manual/project/project_meshes.html.title: Meshes
manual/project/project_meshes.html.body:
Meshes
This section shows the meshes associated with the project/scenario that have been generated by using the features included in the pre-processing module of Ioata or imported from mesh files generated by a CAD software. The "Meshes" accordion shows the following information per mesh (see Figure 9):

Name: name provided by the user to indentify the mesh.
Type: format of the mesh (stl, stp, p4s, ...)
Filename: name of the file that contains the data of the mesh.
Scenario: name of the scenario if the mesh is associated with a scenario.
Modfied: latest modification date of the mesh. 

 
Figure 9 - "Meshes" section at "Project" page 
Importing a Mesh from a File
Users can import meshes into the project by clicking on the Import button located at the right corner of accordion (see Figure 9). A pop-up window will be shown in order introduce the following fields for the mesh:

Name: users needs to provide a name for the mesh.
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the mesh.
Scenario (optional): users can associate the mesh to an existent scenario of the project.
File: the icon located at the right side opens a file browser window that allows users to select the mesh file to be imported.

The following mesh formats can be imported into Iota:

Stereolithography Format (.stl)
STEP (ISO-10303) (.step)
GiD Ascii format (.msh)
3ds Max File (.3ds)
Wavefront OBJ (.obj)
Stanford Polygon Library (.ply)
Allegorithmic Substance Painter Scene (.assbin and .assxml)

 
Figure 10 - Import Mesh window

manual/project/project_files.html.title: Files
manual/project/project_files.html.body:
Files
This section shows the files and scripts associated with the project/scenario. The "Files" accordion shows the following information per file (see Figure 13):

Name: name provided by the user to indentify the mesh.
Type: Files are grouped into two different types:
Scripts: python script files (.py).
Other: any other file to be associated with the project.


Filename: name of the file on the hard drive.
Scenario: name of the scenario if the file is associated with a scenario.
Modfied: latest modification date of the file/script. 

 
Figure 13 - "Files" section of Iota
Importing a Script/File
Users can import files or scripts into the project/scenario by clicking on the "Import" button located at the right corner of accordion (see Figure 13). A pop-up window will be shown in order introduce the following fields for the file/script:

Name: users needs to provide a name for the file/script.
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the file/script.
Scenario (optional): users can associate the file/script to an existent scenario of the project.
Type: users can select between two type of files:
Scripts: files with extension .py.   
Other: any other kind of file that it is not a script.


File: the icon located at the right side opens a file browser window that allows users to select the file/script to be imported.

 
Figure 14 - Import File window

manual/project/project_variables.html.title: Variables
manual/project/project_variables.html.body:
Variables
This sections shows the list of variables defined by the user for the project (see Figure 15). These variables are common for all the scenarios contained in the project and for each one of them the variables can take different values. 
For each variable the following information is shown:

Name: name provided by the user to indenty the variable.
Type: Iota allows users to define three different type of variables:
Manual: the values of the variable for each scnenario are manually assigned by the user.
Built-in: the values of the variables for each scenario are assigned using a built-in script provided by Iota.
User-defined: the values of the variables for each scenario are assigned using a built-in script provided by Iota.


Script: scripts used for to calculate the value of the variable for each scenario (not applycable for variable of type "Manual").
Description: description provided for the user for the variable.
Modified: latest modified date for the variable.

 
Figure 15 - "Variables" section at "Project" page
Creating a new variable
Users can create new variables by using the "Create" button located at the top right corner of the accordion. A pop-up window will be shonw in order introduce the following fields for the variable:

Name: users needs to provide a name for the variable. 
Description (optional): users can provide a description for the variable.
Type: users can use the combo box to select between: Manual, Built-in and User-Defined.
Script: the comnbox box allows users to select the script to use for variables of type "Built-in" and "User-Defined". 

 
Figure 16 - Create Variable window
Calculating variables' values in Batch mode
Iota provides a batch feature in order to automatically evaluate the variables for all the scenarios contained in a project. This feature is avaible for those variables of type "Built-in" and "User-Defined" by clicking on "Calculate" button that is shown when users are hovering the variable's row (see Figure 15). Once the batch calculation has been conducted for all the scenario of the project, the software shows a pop-up window to inform the user.

manual/project/project_list_scenarios.ht.title: List of Scenarios
manual/project/project_list_scenarios.ht.body:
List of Scenarios
This section shows the list of the scenarios contained in the project. The following basic information of each scenario is shonw in the list:

Name: name assigned to the scenario.
Description: brief description of the scenario.
Created: date of creation of the scenario.
Modified: latest date when the scenario was modified.

 
Figure 17 - "Scenarios" section at the "Project" page
Loading a Scenario
Users can load a scenario by means of the Load button that shows up when users are hovering over the list of scenarios (see Figure 17). After clicking on the Load button, the scenario will be autotmatically loaded and the "Scenario" page will be shown on the screen.
Creating a New Scenario
Users can create new scenarios by using the button Create located at the top righ corner of the list of the scenarios at the project page (see Figure 17). After clicking on the button Create, a pop-up window is shown in order to introduce the following information for the new scenario:

Name: users need to provide a name for the scenario.
Description (optional): users can provide a brief description for the scenario.

 
Figure 18 - Create Scenario window
Cloning a Scenario
Users can clone a scenario in order to create a new scenario with the same settings that the cloned one:

Click on the scenario to be cloned from the list of scenarios. 
Click on the button Clone located at the top righ corner of the list of the scenarios. 
The "Clone Scenario" window shows up in order to introduce the following information for the new scenario:

Name: user need to provide a name for the scenario (by default the name of the scenario to be cloned is shown).
Description (optional): users can provide a brief description for the scenario (by default the description of the scenario to be cloned is shown).



 
Figure 19 - Clone Scenario window

manual/project/Batch_processing.html.title: Batch-processing
manual/project/Batch_processing.html.body:
Batch-proccessing
Users can use the "Batch processing" feature provided on the top right corner of the list of scenarios in order to run the coarse-graining analysis in a batch mode for multiple scenarios.
ToDo: Description of the batch processing

manual/scenario/scenario_intro.html.title: Scenario
manual/scenario/scenario_intro.html.body:
Scenario
The "Scenario" page provides information about the assets associated with the current scenario. The structure of the page is similar to the "Project" page (see Figure 20):

Title and Description of the scenario. 
Global: this section shows rectangular accordions for the different type of assets associated with the 
scenario:
Datasets
Screenshots
Graphs
Videos
Files


Variables: this section shows the list of project's variables and their values for the current scenario.
Thumbnail: users can select an image to be used as thumbnail for the scenario. 
Additional information:
User Name: name of the user who created the project.
Created Date: project's creation date.
Last Modified: Latest data when the project was modified.
Tags



 
Figure 20 - Overview of the "Scenario" page
Editing the Info of a Scenario
The basic info of the scenario ("Title", "Description" and "Tags") can be edited by using the option "Edit Scenario". Users can access to this options clicking on the "More" button located at the rigth side of the page (see section 5 in Figure 20). 
Deleting a Scenario
Users can delete an existing scenario from their database by means of the option "Delete Scenario". This option is accessible after clicking on the "More" button located at the right page (see section 5 in Figure 20) 
Updating the variables' values for the current scenario
Users can update the value of the variables shown in the scenario by clicking on the button Edit (for "Manual" variables) or on the button Calculate (for "User-Defined" and "Bulit-in" in variables). These buttons are shown when users are hovering around the listed variables.

manual/pre/pre_intro.html.title: Pre-processing
manual/pre/pre_intro.html.body:
Pre-processing
Users can access to the pre-processing module by means of "Pre" tab located on the the left hand side menu. This tab is enabled once the users load a scenario. Figure 21 shwows the appeareance of the pre-processing module:

List of Meshes: This section shows the list of meshes that user is currently working with, 
Meshing operations: 
This section allows users to perform different operations with the meshes. It is composed of the following tabs:
Rotate
Translate 
Scale
Repair
Generate


Rendering area
Views toolbar
Bottom toolbar:
Save: it allows users to save the meshes to a file.

manual/pre/cretaing-a-simple-geometry.ht.title: Cretaing a Simple Geometry
manual/pre/cretaing-a-simple-geometry.ht.body:
Creating a Simple Geometry
Users can create simple geometries by using the button Create located at the top left corner of the "Pre" module (see Figure 22):

Name: users need to provide a name for the geometry to be created.
Type: users can select among different simple geometries:
Line
Circle
Rectangle
Cuboid
Cylinder



 
Figure 22 - Create a Simple Geometry window

manual/pre/create_line.html.title: Line
manual/pre/create_line.html.body:
Creating a Line
This feature creates a line represented as a mesh compososed of segments/line elements:

Init Point: starting point of the line.
End Point: ending point of the line.
Element Size: length of the segments of the line. 

 
Figure 23 - Create a Line window

manual/pre/create_circle.html.title: Circle
manual/pre/create_circle.html.body:
Creating a Circle
This feature allows users to create circle represented as a mesh compososed of triangular elements:

Direction: Users can select between pre-defined directions (X, Y or Z) or a custom direction for the normal to the circle.
Normal: normal vector to the surface of the circle (only applicable for custom direction).
Centre: center point of the circle.
Radius: radius of the circle.
Element Size: target length of the edges of the triangular elements of the circle.

 
Figure 23 - Create a Circle window

manual/pre/create_rectangle.html.title: Rectangle
manual/pre/create_rectangle.html.body:

Normal: normal vector to the surface of the rectangle (only applicable for custom direction).
Origin: reference point that corresponds to the corner defining the local origin of the rectangle.
Length: size of the rectangle along the axis that follows the selected normal direction1.
Width: size of the rectangle along the axis that follows the direction for the length1.
*Element Size: target length of the edges of the triangular elements of the rectangle.

manual/pre/create_cylinder.html.title: Cylinder
manual/pre/create_cylinder.html.body:
Creating a Cylinder
This feature creates a cylinder represented as a mesh composed of tethrahedral elements:

Direction: Users can select between pre-defined directions (X, Y or Z) or a custom direction for the normal to the base of the cylinder .
Normal: normal vector to the base of the cylinder (only applicable for custom direction).
Base centre: location of the center point of the base.
Radius: radius of the cylinder.
Height: size of the cylinder along the normal direction to the base.
Element Size: target length of the edges of the tetrahedral elements of the cylinder.

manual/pre/Load_Mesh.html.title: Loading a Mesh
manual/pre/Load_Mesh.html.body:
Loading a Mesh into Pre-Processing
Users can load meshes into the pre-processing module by clicking on Load Mesh button (see Figure 27). This button gives access to the list of meshes that are associated with the current scenariro and/or the current project. In order to load a mesh from the list, users just need to click on the mesh to be loaded. Furthermore, users can also load meshes by using the option "Import Mesh from File".
 
Figure 27 - "Load Mesh" window of the pre-processing module.

manual/pre/Fill_Holes_Surface.html.title: Filling holes on a Surface Mesh
manual/pre/Fill_Holes_Surface.html.body:
Filling Holes of a Surface Mesh
This feature allows users to fill the holes of a loaded/imported surface mesh in order to create a closed/water-tight mesh (see Figure 30):

Select an open surface mesh from the list of meshes shown at the top left side of the window by clicking on its name. Alternatively, users can also select a mesh by using the selection mode on the Views toolbar and clicking on the mesh rendered on the screen.
Select one of the options from the Fill Surface Holes section:
Automatic Merge: the mesh patches created to fill the holes of the mesh will be automatically merged into the original mesh.
Patch as Mesh: the mesh patches created to fill the holes of the mesh will shown as individual sub-meshes (one per path) of the original mesh.


Click on Apply button.  

 
Figure 30 - Fill Surface Holes feature of the Pre-processing module
An example of this feature is shown in Figure 31. The image on the left side shows the initial surface mesh of drum with two holes. The image on the right side shows the resulting surface mesh after using the feature Fill Surface Holes.  
 
Figure 31 - Example of the application of Fill Surface Holes feature of the Pre-processing module. Left: Intial open surface mesh with holes. Right: Initial mesh where the holes haven been closed.

Note: The generated closed/watertight mesh can be later used to generate volume mesh.

manual/pre/Generate_Volume_Mesh.html.title: Generating\/Re-meshing a volume mesh
manual/pre/Generate_Volume_Mesh.html.body:
Generating a Volume Mesh
This feature allows users to generate volume meshes from a closed surface mesh or to re-mesh/modify the discretization (element size) of an existing volume mesh:

Select a volume mesh or closed surface mesh from the list of meshes shown at the top left side of the window by clicking on its name. Alternatively, users can also select the mesh by using the selection mode on the Views toolbar and clicking on the mesh rendered on the screen.
Introduce the target value in the Element Size field for the mesh discretization.
Click on Generate button.  

  
Figure 34 - Generate Volume Mesh feature from the pre-processing module.

manual/pre/Generate_Surface_Mesh.html.title: Remeshing a surface mesh
manual/pre/Generate_Surface_Mesh.html.body:
Generating a Surface Mesh
This feature allows users to re-mesh/modify the dicretization (element size) of an existing surface mesh:

Select a surface mesh from the list of meshes shown at the top left side of the window by clicking on its name. Alternatively, users can also select a surface mesh by using the selection mode on the Views toolbar and clicking on the mesh rendered on the screen.
Introduce the target value in the Element Size field for the mesh discretization.
Click on Generate button.  

 
Figure 33 - Generate Surface Mesh feature from the pre-processing module.

manual/post/post_intro.html.title: Post-processing
manual/post/post_intro.html.body:
Post-processing
The post-processing module of Iota allows the users to visualise the results contained in the datasets and investigate the data by means of several post-processing tools. The following sections can be indentified in the post-processing module (see Figure 58: 

Rendering List: This section shows the list of items (meshes and/or particles) that are currently loaded in the post-processing module.
Tools menu: 
Results: allows users to select the results to be visualised.
Tools: allows users to perform post-processing operations with the results.
Cut Plane
Line Variation
Point Evolution
Integrals
Statistics
Stream/Path




Rendering area
Views toolbar
Animation toolbar
Bottom toolbar:
Screenshot: it allows users to automatically create an screenshot of the rendering area.



 
Figure 58 - Post-processing module

manual/coarse_graining/coarse_graining_i.title: Coarse-graining
manual/coarse_graining/coarse_graining_i.body:
Introduction
In most cases where the Discrete Element Method (DEM) is used, it is necessary to carry out some averaging of the data to a scale more representative of what is required.
As such it is quite common for spatial averaging, temporal averaging, or both, to be applied to the DEM data.
To aid the process, a toolbox for the processing of DEM data both temporally and spatially has been implemented at Particle Analytics.
The toolbox has been developed to support many software packages (such as EDEM, PFC, DEMPack and LAMMPS) and provides a simple interface for the averaging
process for the large datasets that DEM simulations produce.
The toolbox provides both a coarse graining method for projecting the results onto a continuum field.
Some of the results are shown in Figure 36.
The coarse-grained density ρ is provided by equation:

where 

r is a point in space where the values are to be evaluated, 
ri(t) is a vector to the centre of mass of the ith particle at a given timestep t, 
mi is that particle's mass, and
φ is the coarse graining function which is subject to the condition of its integral over space being unity.

The coarse-grained velocity V is provided from equation 

where p is the coarse-grained momentum density.
The stress tensor is given by equation

where fijα is the interaction force between two particles, rijβ is the branch vector, s is the integral of the branch vector and v' is the fluctuating velocity of the particle.
 
Figure 36 - Iota-post toolbox in use - Post-processing on a fluidized bed. a) Particles visualization.
b) Spatial averaged density. c) Spatial and temporal averaged density over 20 sec.

manual/coarse_graining/cg_setting_cg.htm.title: Coarse-granining module
manual/coarse_graining/cg_setting_cg.htm.body:
Coarse-graining module
Users can access to the coarse-graining module by means of Coarse graining tab located on the the left hand side menu. This tab is enabled once the users load a scenario. Figure 37 shwows the appeareance of the coarse-graining module:

List of Meshes
This section shows the list of meshes where the discrete DEM data will be projects by means of the coarse-graining processing. It also allows users to change the color and render mode of the meshes. 
Coarse-grainning settings
This section allows users to defined the settings for the coarse-graining processing. It is composed of three different tabs:
Input
Averaging 
Output


Rendering area

Coarse-graining processing control
Save: it allows users to save the settings of the coarse-graining analysis.
Start: it launch the coarse-graining processing. Note that it will also save the settings of the coarse- graining analysis.

manual/coarse_graining/cg_Loading_Mesh.h.title: Loading a Mesh
manual/coarse_graining/cg_Loading_Mesh.h.body:
Loading a Mesh into Coarse-graining
Users can load meshes into the coarse-graining module by clicking on Load Mesh button (see Figure 38). This button gives access to a list of meshes that are associated with the current scenario and project. Users just need to click on one of the listed meshes in order to load it.  Furthermore, users can also load meshes by using the option "Import Mesh from File".
 
Figure 38 - "Load Mesh" window of the coarse-graining module

manual/coarse_graining/cg_Input.html.title: Input
manual/coarse_graining/cg_Input.html.body:
Input
This section is used for the definiton of the DEM data will be processed. The input DEM datata can be selected and filtered by time range, steps frequency and more advanced options (see Figure 40).
 
Figure 40 - Input section of coarse-graining module.
Input DEM data
This section allows users to select the input DEM data to be processed. The icon located at the right side of the this field give access to a list of options to select the input DEM data (see Figure 41):

Selected DEM data: it corresponds to the current selected input DEM data. Also, users can click on it in order to edit the name and other options of the current selected input DEM data.
 Current Scenario DEM Dataset: Users can see here if a DEM dataset is already associated with the current scneario.
Project DEM dataset: Users can see here list of DEM datasets asociated with the current project.
Read from DEM solver files: it allows users to select the input DEM data directly from different types of DEM output files:
EDEM 2017
LIGGGHTS-DUMP
P4X



 
Figure 41 - Input DEM data section of coarse-graining module.
Uses Contacts
Users can specify if they want to use the DEM contact data for the coarse-graining processing by activated the check box:

Particle: it refers to the particle-particle contacts data.
Wall: it referes to the particle-wall contacts data.  

Use Geometry
Users can specify if they want to include the surface geometries/walls into the output datasets.  
Time Steps
Users can define the range of the time-steps to be processed by the coarse-graing:

All: if activated, all the time-steps from the input DEM data are proccessed.
Start: if All is not activated, it defines the time at which coase-granning module shoud begin processing the input DEM data.     
End: if All is not activated, it defines the time at which coase-granning module shoud stop processing the input DEM data.     

Frequency
Users can choose the frequency for reading the time steps from the input DEM data.
Pre-Filters
Users can choose different types of filters that are applied to the input DEM data before being processing by the coarse-graining module:

Overwrite Groups by Particles Size
Filter Group ID
Overwrite Velocity
Overwrite Groups

manual/coarse_graining/cg_Averaging.html.title: Averaging
manual/coarse_graining/cg_Averaging.html.body:
Averaging settings for Coarse-graining
This section is used for the definiton of the settting for the averaging processes to be performed by the coarse-graining module:

Temporal averaging: section to set the definition of the temporal averaging process.
Spatial averaging: section to set the definition of the spatial averaging process.
Advanced: users can add advanced analyses to be performed during the coarse-graining calculation:
Particle Group Concentration
Surface/Wall Analysis
Residence Time



 
Figure 49 - "Averaging" section of coarse-graining module.

manual/coarse_graining/cg_Output.html.title: Output
manual/coarse_graining/cg_Output.html.body:
Output
This section is used to define the output generation from the coarse-graning modules. This tabs exposes the output of special results for the coarse-grainig and DEM datasets, allows the user to scale the results and set post-anlyses to be performed over the coarse-graining results.
 
Figure 55 - Output section of coarse-graining module.
Output Nane
Users need to provide a name that will be used for naming the coarse-graining (and optionally DEM) dataset generated by the coarse-graining module.
Default Location
This allows users to select where the outputs of the coarse-graning module will be stored. If Default Location is activated in the outputs will be stored in the default folders of the current scenario. If Default Location is not activated, users can click on the icon "open folder" in order select the output directory.
Scale Results
When it is activated, it allows the users to introduce a number to scale all the results from the coarse-graining output. This option, combined with the spatial integrals, is useful when calculating the average in a certain direction or plane. The most common uses of the Scale Results option are:

A change of units in the model.

The calculation of the average value in a certain direction/plane. This is performed in combination with the 1D/2D integrals.


Create DEM Datasets
When it is activated, the coarse-graining module generates a DEM dataset based on the input DEM data previously specified by the user in the Input tab of the coarse-graining. Furthermore, users can select the results to be generated for the DEM dataset.
 
Figure 56 - List of results for the output DEM dataset generated by the coarse-graining module.

Particle Results: results related with the individual particle properties.

Mass
Volume
Size: radius for spherical particles. In the case of non-spherical particles, the size corresponds to the radius if a sphere of a volume equivalent to the volume of the particle.
Velocity
Custom Properties: any other particle properties that is not included in the previous list.


Contact Results: results derived from the contact data.

Particle Total Force: total force on the particles (i.e., unbalanced particle force).
Contact Total Force: total force comming from the contacts interaction.
Normal force: force magnitude in the normal direction of the contacts (i.e., direction of the branch vector).
Tangential force: force magnitude in the tangential direction of the contacts.
Mobilized friction: ratio of the Tangential force to the Normal force of the contacts.
Coordination Number: Number of contacts of each particle.  



Coarse Graining Output
When it is activated, the coarse-graining module generates a coarse-grainig dataset based on the processing of the  input DEM data previously specified by the user in the Input tab of the coarse-graining. Furthermore, users can select the results to be generated for the coarse-graining dataset.
 
Figure 57 - List of results for the output coarse-graining dataset generated by the coarse-graining module.

Particle Results: coarse-graining results computed based on the particles data:
Density: bulk or apparent density.
Solid Fraction
Size
Momentum
Velocity
Number of particles
Custom properties: spatial averaged values of any custom properties contained in the input DEM data.




Stress Analysis Results: coarse-grainig results computed from the contact information and/or related with particles stress calculation:
Total Stress: stress tensor including contact and kinetic stress. 
Kinetic Stess
Symmetric Stress
Hydrostatic Pressure
Deviatoric Stress
Mobilized friction
Number of contacts




Wall/Surface Results: coarse-graining results generated by the Surface/Wall analysis available in the section Advanced of the Averaging tab of the coarse-graining settings:
Pressure
Drag Force



Post-Analysis
Users can add here analysis based on the output results of the coarse-graining dataset and/or DEM dataset. The analysis can be provided by Iota (Built-in) or users can use their own python scripts by using the API provided with Iota.
Mixing
An example of a analysis provided with Iota is the Mixing Analysis using the Lacey mixig index. Adding this analysis to the Post-Analysis sectiong, the software will automatically create and import into the system the following graphs:

Lacey mixig index: temporal evolution of the Lacey Mixing index. If the number of particles group is larger than two, the graph will contain a trace per particle group.
Mixing Concentraction: temporal evolution of the average cocentration of each particle group. The graphs includes a trace per particle group.
Mixing Components: temporal evolution of the particle group concentration variance, the variance for a segregated mixture and the variance for a fully random mixture (one trace per component). If the number of particles group is larger than two, a graph per particle group will be generated.
